            <div class="prose max-w-none" x-show="lang === 'en'" x-cloak>
                <h2>Q1: What's the Difference Between 'High-Volume' and 'High-Converting' Creatives?</h2>
<p>In simple terms: <strong>high-volume measures traffic, high-converting measures revenue.</strong></p>
<p>High-volume creatives attract impressions and clicks—high CTR, low CPM, fast spending. High-converting creatives bring users who actually pay or complete target actions—high CVR, reasonable CPA, positive ROAS.</p>
<p>The problem is these two dimensions often diverge in Meta ad accounts.</p>
<p>A utility app team tested 30 creatives. Eight had CTR above 2% but CVR below 0.5%—zero monetization. Meanwhile, two creatives with only 0.8% CTR but 5% CVR contributed 80% of revenue.</p>
<p>During review, you must separate these two dimensions.</p>
<hr />
<h2>Q2: Why Do Many High-Volume Creatives End Up with Poor ROI?</h2>
<p>The core reason: <strong>the creative attracts clicks but not target users.</strong></p>
<p>For example, an e-commerce ad using "starting at $1" or "lowest price online" as hooks achieved 3% CTR with lightning-fast spending, but only 0.2% conversion rate—well below the 1% average. Users clicked expecting $1 items, found otherwise, and bounced immediately.</p>
<p>These creatives overpromise, creating misalignment between user expectations and reality. The traffic attracted are price-sensitive deal-seekers, not genuine target customers.</p>
<p>Quick check: if CTR is high but conversions drop sharply at a specific funnel stage, you likely have a high-volume, low-converting creative.</p>
<hr />
<h2>Q3: Which Metric Combinations Should I Focus on During Creative Review?</h2>
<p>Check metrics by phase with different weights.</p>
<p><strong>Phase 1: Days 1-3</strong><br />
- Focus: Is CTR &gt;1.5%? Is CPM below industry average?<br />
- Purpose: Can the creative pass platform and user acceptance?</p>
<p><strong>Phase 2: Days 3-7</strong><br />
- Focus: Is 7-day ROAS &gt;1.0? Is paid conversion rate &gt;1%?<br />
- Purpose: Do users brought by this creative have payment willingness?</p>
<p><strong>Phase 3: Days 7-30</strong><br />
- Focus: Does 30-day LTV exceed acquisition cost? Is user retention healthy?<br />
- Purpose: Do these users have long-term value?</p>
<p>In practice, build three tracking tables: traffic metrics, conversion metrics, and revenue metrics—cross-reference all three.</p>
<hr />
<h2>Q4: Should I Pause or Optimize Creatives That Are High-Volume but Low-Converting?</h2>
<p><strong>Decision criteria: check the CPM-to-CPA ratio.</strong></p>
<p>If CPM is low (&lt;$8), traffic costs are favorable. Try optimizing landing pages or adjusting targeting countries to improve conversion. If CPM is already high (&gt;$15), the creative's traffic-side competitiveness is declining—you should pause it.</p>
<p>A cross-border e-commerce team's approach: observe for 3 days first. For creatives with CTR&gt;2% but CVR&lt;1%, attempt optimization—change CTA button color, test different landing page entry points, adjust audience targeting. If optimization fails,果断 pause on day 7 to stop budget waste.</p>
<hr />
<h2>Q5: How to Filter Out 'High-Volume, Low-Converting' Creatives During Testing?</h2>
<p>The key is small-scale validation before full-scale running—only scale creatives that convert well.</p>
<ol>
<li><strong>A/B testing phase</strong>: Run 2-3 creatives simultaneously with $20-50 Ad Set budget, check CTR and CVR after 24-48 hours</li>
<li><strong>Elimination phase</strong>: Creatives with CTR&gt;1.5% but CVR&lt;1% are directly eliminated—do not proceed to next round</li>
<li><strong>Validation phase</strong>: Creatives passing both CTR and CVR thresholds continue with $100-200 budget for 3 more days, focusing on whether CPA stays within 1/3 of LTV</li>
<li><strong>Scaling phase</strong>: Only truly good creatives with passing CPA move to Campaign-level scaling</li>
</ol>
<p>A casual gaming team following this filtering process saw hit rate increase from 30% to 55%, with wasteful spending reduced by 60%.</p>
<hr />
<h2>Q6: What Should a Creative Review Report Include?</h2>
<p>A proper review report answers three questions:</p>
<p><strong>How did the metrics perform?</strong><br />
List actual values and benchmarks for spend, CPM, CTR, CVR, CPA, ROAS in table format.</p>
<p><strong>Why did they perform well or poorly?</strong><br />
Analyze from three angles: creative level (copy, visuals, CTA), audience level (age, region, interest targeting), and landing page level (load speed, relevance, conversion path).</p>
<p><strong>What comes next?</strong><br />
Clarify which creatives to continue running, which to optimize, which to pause, and the testing plan for the next phase.</p>
<p>Review is not about finding excuses afterward—it's about accurately directing budget toward truly profitable creatives in the next round.</p>
